1.Introduction¶
This report aims to explore multiclass image classification problems, specifically using the MNIST dataset. Following François Chollet's universal workflow from "Deep Learning with Python," we strive for a systematic approach to develop, evaluate, and refine our model.























2.Problem statement and Dataset¶
We tackle the MNIST dataset's classification challenge, aiming to accurately categorize 28x28 pixel images of handwritten digits into one of ten classes (digits 0 through 9). Given the stationary nature of this problem, we anticipate reliable model performance across similar unseen data.























2.1 Hypothesis and Dataset Rationale¶






















I theorize that a strong predictive relationship exists between an image's pixel values and the label it represents, enabling precise classification. This theory rests on the idea that a model can learn patterns within the pixel data to differentiate between digit classes. I chose the TensorFlow-provided MNIST dataset because of its  diversity and size, which support effective model training. It includes 60,000 training images and 10,000 for testing, each digit (0-9) represented in a roughly 6000:1000 split within the training and testing sets.


Because the MNIST dataset has balanced class distribution, accuracy will be the main way to judge the model. Precision and recall are also important, especially when there's class imbalance, but less essential in this scenario. Still, they'll help analyze the model's performance, like finding biases towards certain classes or if different classes have heavily varying false-positive/negative costs.























3. Establishing an evaluation method: Hold-Out Validation¶
To ensure that a rigorious and fair assessment of my model's performance is employed, i will employ hold-out validation as the evaluation protocol. This method shall involve setting aside a portion of the training data to create a validation set,which is not used during the model's learning phase but instead plays a role of evaluating the model's predictions and monitoring of its performance during the training process.

This is achieved via Tensorflow's to_categorical() utility function.

5. Model Development and Baseline Establishment¶
In adherence to Chollet's DLWP, surpassing the baseline performance in MNIST image classification embodies not just exceeding a mere 10% accuracy-- which represents the threshold of random chance given ten classes-- but substantially excelling beyond this point.
My goal is to create a neural network model that leverages the structured relationships between the pixel values and their corresponding values to significantly exceed this baseline.


Architectural choices:


Last-Layer Activation: The softmax function is selected for its proficiency in outputting a probability distribution across the ten classes, aligning perfectly with the multiclass nature of my task.


Loss Function: Categorical crossentropy is my choice here, apt for evaluating the accuracy of predictions across multiple categories by comparing the predicted probability distribution against the actual distribution of labels.


Optimizer: RMSprop, known for its effectiveness in adjusting the learning rate automatically, ensures my model trains efficiently, making it a preferred optimizer for our setup.

























Reference from page 114 of DLWP "Choosing the right last-layer activation and loss function for your model"

Before diving into model building, its eseential to set the baseline for comparison. For this, i will consider a Naive Majority Class Baseline, which assumes the most frequent class in the training set as prediction for all instances. This approach give an initial benchmark for the model's performance.

def visualize_training_loss(hist_data):
    """
    Visualizes training and validation loss.

    Parameters:
    hist_data (History): Training history of the model.
    """
    train_loss, val_loss = hist_data.history['loss'], hist_data.history['val_loss']
    epochs = range(1, len(train_loss) + 1)

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    plt.plot(epochs, train_loss, 'b-', label='Training Loss')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'r', label='Validation Loss')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

def visualize_training_accuracy(hist_data):
    """
    Visualizes training and validation accuracy.

    Parameters:
    hist_data (History): Training history of the model.
    """
    train_accuracy, val_accuracy = hist_data.history['accuracy'], hist_data.history['val_accuracy']
    epochs = range(1, len(train_accuracy) + 1)

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    plt.plot(epochs, train_accuracy, 'b-', label='Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_accuracy, 'r', label='Validation Accuracy')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

7. Developing an overfitting model¶
To ensure our model performs optimally, we need to find the sweet spot between overfitting and underfitting. Here are three ways to check for that:


    

  • Add layers: Increasing model complexity can help it learn more intricate
patterns
    • 

  • Make layers bigger: Expanding layers (more neurons) provides the model with greater capacity to capture relationships.
    • 

  • Train for more epochs: Additional training allows the model to refine its understanding of the data
    •

Now that a baseline model and an overfitting counterpart have been established, the next phase involves systematic hyperparameter tuning.
 Strategies include:


    

  • Selective Neuron Deactivation: Evaluation of dropout techniques to encourage
generalization.
    • 

  • Layer Modifications: Exploration of the effects of adding or removing layers on performance and overfitting tendencies.
    • 

  • Regularization Implementation: Application of L1 and/or L2 regularization to constrain model complexity.
    • 

  • Hyperparameter Optimization: Exploration of adjustments to units per layer, learning rate, and other hyperparameters.
    • 



Through these processes, it will help me develop a acceptable model configuration where it is a good fit and the training and validation loss both decreases and stablizes at a specific point.























8.1 Reducing the number of Epochs¶
i will attempt to decrease the number of training epochs for the model and observe how it impacts accuracy, because the base model had a greater validation accuracy with fewer epochs.


To assist us in achieving this, a function has been developed that returns the training epoch with the lowest validation loss.



















In [28]:



     


def find_optimal_epoch(training_history):
    """
    Identifies the optimal epoch number where the validation loss was minimum.

    Parameters:
    training_history (dict): A dictionary containing the training history of the model,
                             specifically 'val_loss' for the validation loss over epochs.

    Returns:
    int: The epoch number (1-indexed) where the validation loss was at its lowest.
    """

    # Check if 'val_loss' is in the history dictionary
    if 'val_loss' not in training_history:
        print("Validation loss not found in training history.")
        return None

    # Find the index of the minimum validation loss
    min_loss_index = np.argmin(training_history['val_loss'])

    # Convert to 1-indexed epoch number
    optimal_epoch = min_loss_index + 1

    print(f"Minimum validation loss reached in epoch: {optimal_epoch}")
    return optimal_epoch

8.2 Dropout Regularisation Application¶
Dropout Regularisation is an approach whereby certain nodes in each layer is randomly dropped or "disregarded". This is known as dropout and is typically implemented by adding dropout layers into the neural network architecture. The main benefit is its effective in reduce overfitting as it ensures that no units are codependant on each other.



















In [47]:

8.3 L2 Regularisation¶
In the next model,i will employ L2 regularisation, which will impose a penalty on the magnitude of the coefficients. This technique discourages the model from relying too heavily on any individiual features by shrinking the weights, therefore mitigating the risk of overfitting and improves the models ability to generalise its predictions to new data.



















In [36]:



     


RegularisationModel = Model_Sequence([
                    Flatten(input_shape=(28, 28)),
                    Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.01)),#adding regularizer
                    Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.01)),
                    Dropout(0.5), # Add dropout
                    Dense(48, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.01)),
                    Dense(16, activation='relu'),
                    Dense(10, activation='softmax')
], name='RegularisationModel')

RegularisationModel.summary()

RegularisationModel.compile(optimizer='rmsprop',
              loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

RegularisationModel_history = RegularisationModel.fit(X_train_final, y_train_final,
                                    epochs=optimal_epoch_number, batch_size=64,
                                    validation_data=(X_val, y_val)
                                    )

9.Comparison & Conclusion¶
Throughout the model training process, I implemented several strategies to achieve a good fit between training and validation performance. Tuning the models to optimize the parameters was the most time-intensive part, especially due to the lengthy epoch durations required for training.


Despite rigorous experimentation with different regularization methods and hyperparameter adjustments, the models demonstrated a tendency to overfit, which was sensitive to even minor changes in the model architecture.


Comparing the three approaches—reducing the number of epochs, implementing dropout, and applying L2 regularization—the model that combined reduced epochs and a dropout rate of 0.3 emerged as the most accurate.


    

  • The Epoch Model showed an improvement when we reduced the epochs from 20 to 7, which helped to mitigate overfitting by reducing the training process before the model could memorize the training data.
    

    • 

  • The Dropout Model introduced a dropout rate of 0.3 after the initial dense layers, which helped in preventing over-reliance on any particular neuron, thus reducing overfitting. This model showed a better fit compared to the Epoch Model, with a closer convergence of training and validation loss.
    

    • 

  • The Regularization Model applied L2 regularization to penalize large weights, coupled with dropout. The results indicated an even better fit, as reflected by the smooth convergence of the training and validation loss, suggesting that the combined effect of L2 regularization and dropout was beneficial.
    

    •

While the models developed in this report has shown some sort of promising result, continous improvement is needed for achieving optimal performance. This could involve eperimenting with different actation functions or exploration into advanced optimization algorithms such as Adam or Nadam, which may offer better convergence rates.
